<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-435-808  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 435 808.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  June 22 1989 v15 n13 p27(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Processing without fingers; successful AO is more than justautomating console operators. (automated operations)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shuflin, Joel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>One obstacle to efficient data processing automation is theselective automation of certain functions over tasks that continueto be performed by people.andP;  Automation tools that replace consoleoperators, for example, are frequently chosen over tools thataddress different manual components of data processing.andP;  Accordingto one automation expert, the benefits of console automation isnegligible when compared to the advantages of automating otherprocessing tasks.andP;  Perhaps the biggest barrier to the extensiveuse of automation tools is the reluctance of people to change.andO;Most experts agree that the automation of data processingoperations should be approached with the same strategy as thatwhich is used for application development.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationData ProcessingHuman FactorsMISGuidelines.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>